<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
Two specimens are present in the ZMUC collection under the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Tenthredo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tenthredo germanica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="germanica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Tenthredo germanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Klug, F" journalOrPublisher="Der Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde zu Berlin Magazin fuer die neuesten Entdeckungen in der gesamten Naturkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" refId="B80" refString="Klug, F, 1819. Die Blattwespen (Tenthredo Linn.) der Fabricischen Sammlung. Zoologisches Magazin (herausgegeben von C. R. W. Wiedemann) 1[1817-1819](3): 64-91." title="Die Blattwespen (Tenthredo Linn.) der Fabricischen Sammlung. Zoologisches Magazin (herausgegeben von C. R. W. Wiedemann) 1 [1817 - 1819] (3): 64 - 91." year="1819">Klug (1819)</bibRefCitation>
referred to one of them, which has black legs and an infuscated tip of the abdomen (&quot;Das vorhandene Exemplar hatte schwarze Beine und einen an der Spitze 
<normalizedToken originalValue="schwärzlichen">schwaerzlichen</normalizedToken>
Hinterleib, [...]&quot;). This specimen is selected as the lectotype. It corresponds with the current concept of 
<taxonomicName authority="Panzer, 1801" authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1801" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Dolerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dolerus germanicus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="germanicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Dolerus germanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, e.g. in the shape of the sawsheath (valvula 3) setation. The species needs a thorough revision, because DNA barcoding divides the specimens into two BINs (BOLD:AAI9736 and BOLD:ABV8027) separated by a minimum of over 5% divergence, indicating the possible presence of two distinct species. The two BINs are associated with color differences, of which some appear stable within the cluster and others are variable. Based on about 80 barcoded specimens from Finland, specimens of BOLD:ABV8027 consistently have entirely black hind legs, while those of BOLD:AAI9736 usually have largely orange hind femora and tibiae, although sometimes they are completely black. Additionally, females with a red mesoscutellum always fall in BOLD:AAI9736 and always have red tegulae, pronotum and mesoscutum, whereas in BOLD:ABV8027 the mesoscutellum is always entirely or mostly black, but the tegulae, pronotum and mesoscutum vary from black to red. It is also worth mentioning that the division of specimens into two groups was not reflected in two nuclear genes (POL2 and NaK). Likewise, no useful structural characters have yet been found, but a more detailed systematic study of the male genitalia might be helpful.
</paragraph>
